<br>
Your mention of the term &quot;season&quot; reminded me of a few awkward moments I experienced as I am always /roleplay and folks often want to know how &quot;seasoned&quot; someone is when starting up a group.<br>
<br>
Using the term &quot;season&quot; always seemed so awkward to me because I'd be in a group and thought it a bit weird to say, &quot;hey guys, you know the weather hasn't changed or nothing (all this in RP, of course) and I look just the same as I did just a minute ago, but guess what ?!? I've matured another season!&quot;  ((Sure, people don't change their looks or &quot;skills&quot; much between the day before a birthday and the day of a birthday in real life, but then again, most folks don't celebrate a birthday 3 times in the course of a day...))<br>
<br>
As a warrior, I opted for the expression, &quot;I have faced my trainer 18 times, or I have been tested in the warriors' arena in Halas some 31 times, or - well, you get the idea. Unfortunately, much of the time, no one had any idea what I was talking about, and I would finally give up and say, &quot;I am 18 seasons&quot; ...<br>
<br>
I'm not here to knock anyone's preferred way of expressing - in character - their level, but from a role-playing perspective, I really enjoy it when folks are very creative about communicating their level and class.<br>
<br>
